<br>
Honestly I don't consider your posy too harsh — it's obviously a well thought out response, and I respect that. Ultimately it sounds like the primary hang-up I have is not having a centralk spot to turn to to find a spot for raid organization. But honestly I'm fine with the way that it is set up if it's been working.<br>
<br>
Heck, I'm only level 54 and I defer to the 60+ people and their experience. I agree that epics are not everything, but in most cases they are the most difficult to complete as tyhey require several steps...most times easily organized, but sometimes moe difficult.<br>
<br>
i.e. Phinigal Autopros sometimes needs to be taken down 15-20 times before he drops the wiz epic piece. <br>
<br>
I also didn't want to give the impression that epic raid attendance be a requirement - only if you want to get your own. But again, if this guild has something good going I can live with that for now.<br>
<br>
I know the guild is at the stage - overall - beyond epic raids. <br>
<br>
I appreciate the debate though - it's always good to bring up and toss around subjects like this if they concern you in any way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#Dccfa7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/bamazonguild.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rjs68olds>RJs68Olds</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 840<br> <font color=#2F2F4F>(4/10/03 12:13:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub24.ezboard.com/famazonguildfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=331.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How does raiding work?</span><hr size=1> I do agree that the raid scheduling setup that we have (or more or less don't have)  isn't very effective.  But, every attempt that has been made in the past to organize things into a calendar type system hasn't really changed anything.  In all honesty, the Guild MOTD is by far the best place to put any raid plans.  Nothing has the visibility that the MOTD does.  I'd make a generous guesstimate that even at it's prime, only about 40% of the guild actually visited these boards more than once a month, and that's being very generous.  I'm guessing more like 25%, just look at the number of different names you see here on the boards and compare them to the Guild Window.<br>
<br>
In addition, I'd have to say that every calendar system is doomed to failure when it concerns mobs that are never up for very long.  Go to any major guild's webpage and look for their calendar, they don't have one for the most part, or it's been long abandoned due to it's uselessness.  The only thing they are handy for is all day farm-fest events really.  And even then it's not exactly foolproof because some other guild may have the same idea at the same time you do.<br>
<br>
Instead we, as a guild, should be more ready to organize on targets of opportunity that do pop up through the day.  In the past the major thing that has hurt us is the general lack of motivation when it comes to getting together for a target when it is called.  In my opinion, a lot of the problem lies in the general lack of zone connectivity knowledge.  At 55+ you should know how to get from the nexus to UP, or from CS to ToV. If you don't, there about 1,000,000 places you can go to find maps. And with the UI able to run in a window you have no excuse for getting lost anymore.  Hell, they've even added a map to the UI for most zones used for general travel.  Mobilization is key here, not planning.  <br>
<br>
When we do have a shot at something that drops good loot, we should have druids and wizzies doing pickups and people running as fast as they can to get to the nearest ring/spire.  With PoP and the PoK book system in general, almost every zone is within easy reach.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, Epics are a very personal stepping stone and I think everyone should get theirs.  But, I do not feel it is the responsibility of the guild to get each member their epic.  It is more the responsibility of the person, and the friends he makes along the way.  When I did my epic, about 1/4, maybe 1/2 of the people who came along to kill Faydedar were in Amazon.  I sat there and just asked friends to come over and sit with me throughout the day until I felt there were enough people present to make an attempt.  I ended up with major overkill and it was a very anticlimatic battle.  But, I am proud of it nonetheless <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.cox.net/amazonguild/sigs/nuvarre.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
